<subSubSection lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="21" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="19.[264,1323,1358,1905]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,464,1678,1704]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Description.</emphasis>
Sponge is massive, semispherical, sometimes thickly encrusting, up to 
<number box="[1308,1323,1679,1705]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="8.0">8</number>
long, 
<quantity box="[331,391,1719,1745]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="cm" value="4.0">4 cm</quantity>
wide, 
<quantity box="[480,539,1719,1745]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="cm" value="5.0">5 cm</quantity>
high (
<figureCitation box="[616,685,1719,1745]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[264,368,1684,1708]" captionTargetBox="[347,1256,313,1663]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[347,1259,311,1664]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. Latrunculia, Strongylodesma and Tsitsikamma species in situ: A, Latrunculia lunaviridis sp. nov. (BMNH 1996.7.3.6); B, Latrunculia microacanthoxea sp. nov. (BMNH 1996.7.3.1); C. Latrunculia bellae sp. nov. (BMNH 2003.1.10.1); D, Strongylodesma algoaensis sp. nov. (BMNH 1996.7.3.3); E, Strongylodesma tsitsikammaensis sp. nov. (BMNH 1996.7.3.5); F, Tsitsikamma favus (Holotype, BMNH 1997.7.3.2); G, T. pedunculata sp. nov. (BMNH 2003.1.10.2); H, T. scurra sp. nov. (BMNH 2003.1.10.3)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/168853/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Fig. 
<number box="[671,685,1719,1745]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
H). Texture, compressible internally with a relatively tough thick sandpapery ectosome. Surface crowded with large hollow strap­like oscular fistules, 
<quantity box="[366,494,1799,1825]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="17.5" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="15.0">15–20 mm</quantity>
high, 
<quantity box="[573,658,1799,1825]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="14.0">14 mm</quantity>
wide at base and 
<quantity box="[879,949,1799,1825]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
high at apex, the apex slightly expanded. Scattered between oscules are numerous fungiform areolate porefields, 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="10.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="8.0">8–12 mm</quantity>
high, 
<quantity box="[383,480,1879,1905]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4 mm</quantity>
wide. Colour in life lime green and in preservative dark liver brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[264,1323,283,1110]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,613,283,309]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Spicules. Megascleres—</emphasis>
Styles: Slightly curved, thickened centrally, two sizes; 
<number box="[1279,1323,284,310]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="829.0">829</number>
(
<number box="[272,377,324,350]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="828.0" valueMax="882.0" valueMin="774.0">774–882</number>
) 
<date box="[396,450,324,350]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1924-10">
x 
<quantity box="[421,450,324,350]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="m" value="24.0">24</quantity>
</date>
m; thinner, slightly curved centrally: 
<number box="[928,972,324,350]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="669.0">669</number>
(
<number box="[991,1096,324,350]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="661.5" valueMax="738.0" valueMin="585.0">585–738</number>
) 
<date box="[1114,1168,324,350]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1917-10">
x 
<quantity box="[1139,1168,324,350]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="m" value="17.0">
<specimenCount box="[1139,1168,324,350]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="generic">17</specimenCount>
</quantity>
</date>
m. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Microscleres—</emphasis>
Isochiadiscorhabds (Fig. 
<number box="[684,700,364,390]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="4.0">4</number>
G): With three whorls of conico­cylindrical tubercules, the apex of each tubercular projection is acanthose. The conico­cylindrical tubercules project at 
<number box="[509,538,444,470]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="45.0">45</number>
to the shaft in pairs: 
<number box="[797,826,444,470]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="41.0">41</number>
(
<number box="[843,917,444,470]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="41.5" valueMax="45.0" valueMin="38.0">38–45</number>
) 
<date box="[933,970,444,470]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
x 
<quantity box="[955,970,444,470]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="m" value="8.0">
<specimenCount box="[955,970,444,470]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="generic">8</specimenCount>
</quantity>
</date>
m.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[264,1323,283,1110]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,426,483,509]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Skeleton.</emphasis>
The overall skeleton is dominated by a thick ectosomal envelope of tangential megascleres, 
<quantity box="[469,619,524,550]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.85" metricValueMax="5.4" metricValueMin="2.3" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="m" value="385.0" valueMax="540.0" valueMin="230.0">230–540 m</quantity>
thick, extending up into the large oscular tubes. Within the envelope is a much softer choanosome containing an irregular reticulation of wispy tracts of small styles ranging in width from 
<number box="[708,809,604,630]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="190.0" valueMax="200.0" valueMin="180.0">180–200</number>
µm thick (
<figureCitation box="[939,1010,604,630]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="16.[264,367,1749,1773]" captionTargetBox="[301,1302,451,1738]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[301,1306,449,1739]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 6. Skeletal arrangement within Tsitsikamma spp: A, Tsitsikamma favus Samaai &amp; Kelly, (magnification X 4); B, T. pedunculata sp. nov., (magnification X 10); C, T. scurra sp. nov., (magnification X 4); D, Anisostrongyles in Strongylodesma algoaensis sp. nov.; E, Anisostrongyles in Strongylodesma tsitsikammaensis sp. nov .." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/156905/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Fig. 
<number box="[994,1010,604,630]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
C). Microscleres are abundant throughout the choanosome.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[264,1323,283,1110]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,417,684,710]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Ecology.</emphasis>
The sponge was found on a moderately rugged rocky outcrop beneath kelp about 
<quantity box="[336,411,724,750]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="m" value="150.0">150 m</quantity>
from a ship­wreck, 
<specimenCount box="[648,715,724,750]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="generic">
<quantity box="[648,711,724,750]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="m" value="28.0">28 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[264,1323,283,1110]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,452,764,790]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named for the appearance of the sponge, with elongate, flattened occasionally bent­over oscular fistules, resembling the elongate tasselled extensions on a jester’s hat.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[264,1323,283,1110]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,433,884,910]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Remarks.</emphasis>
Species of 
<taxonomicName box="[570,715,884,909]" class="Demospongiae" family="Latrunculiidae" genus="Tsitsikamma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[570,715,884,909]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Tsitsikamma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very clearly differentiated at the morphological and skeletal level. 
<taxonomicName authority="Samaai &amp; Kelly" authorityName="Samaai &amp; Kelly" box="[489,785,924,950]" class="Demospongiae" family="Latrunculiidae" genus="Tsitsikamma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="favus">
<emphasis box="[489,581,924,949]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">T. favus</emphasis>
Samaai &amp; Kelly
</taxonomicName>
is turquoise, semispherical, extremely tough and multi­chambered, with short surface extensions, while 
<taxonomicName box="[957,1116,964,989]" class="Demospongiae" family="Latrunculiidae" genus="Tsitsikamma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="pedunculat">
<emphasis box="[957,1116,964,989]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">T. pedunculat</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a sp. nov. is pinkish­brown, stalked and bulbous. 
<taxonomicName box="[682,807,1004,1029]" class="Demospongiae" family="Latrunculiidae" genus="Tsitsikamma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="scurra" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[682,807,1004,1029]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">T. scurra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[820,917,1004,1030]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is lime green (preservative­liver brown), thickly encrusting, soft and compressible, with flat hollow oscular fistules. The morphology of the microscleres further differentiates these species.
</paragraph>
